e terms. Additional topics include the Twins Paradox, the physical aspects of the Lorentz-FitzGerald contraction, the constancy of the speed of light, time travel, the direction of time, and more. Introduces nonphysicists to the philosophical foundations of space-time theory Provides a broad historical overview, from Aristotle to Einstein Explains special relativity geometrically, emphasizing the intrinsic structure of space-time Covers the Twins Paradox, Galilean relativity, time travel, and more Requires only basic algebra and no formal knowledge of physics  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aAbsolute rotation.  aAbsolute time and space.  aAcceleration.  aAccelerometer.  aAffine transformation.  aAtomic clock.  aAxiom.  aBucket argument.  aCalculation.  aCaloric theory.  aCartesian coordinate system.  aCauchy surface.  aCircular motion.  aClassical electromagnetism.  aClassical mechanics.  aClock hypothesis.  aClock.  aClosed timelike curve.  aCoordinate system.  aCurvature.  aDiagram (category theory).  aDiagram.  aDiffeomorphism.  aDimension.  aEarth's rotation.  aEarth.  aEinstein field equations.  aElectromagnetic field.  aElectromagnetism.  aEquivalence principle.  aEuclidean geometry.  aEuclidean space.  aEvent horizon.  aExplanation.  aFictitious force.  aGalileo's ship.  aGeneral relativity.  aGeometry.  aGravitational lens.  aGravitational wave.  aGravity.  aHole argument.  aHomogeneous space.  aIdentity of indiscernibles.  aIndeterminism.  aInertial frame of reference.  aInstant.  aIrreversible process.  aIsotropy.  aLight cone.  aLinear equation.  aLorentz transformation.  aMass.  aMathematics.  aMaxwell–Boltzmann distribution.  aMinkowski space.  aM